												<!-- START NEWS AREAS-->
												<table width="90%" border="0" align="center" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0">
													<tr><td valign="top" width="100%">&nbsp;<br>
													<!-- strMainData goes here-->
													<table align='center' cellpadding=5 width='85%'>  <tr><td class='header' bgcolor='black' width='100%'>PALADIN STRATEGIES AND PLAYGUIDES</td></tr>  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'><font class='spti'>BE SNEAKY... FOOL THE CASTERS!</font> - <small>Vladior Singrave [Crusaders of Tempus], Tallon Zek</td></tr>
  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'>We've all experienced the dreaded Caster PK that seems to pick on the poor defensless Tanks. Well, I have had a lot of fun recently, and A lot of Casters haven't. Here is the thing. As a paladin you have a lot of weapons at your disposal, such as Healing, Casting various helpful spells, and most importantly, Lay on Hands. Now the biggest thing to remember when fighting a caster is to not let them no that you are a Paladin. The Wizard, or whichever class it may be, will try to avoid you and blow you into the dirt if he thinks he will be able to, thus burning away all of his precious mana. Stay calm and collected and run around after him acting like a poor defnseless tank running low on life. The caster, not knowing that you are a paladin- hopefully- will use that last bit of mana for that killing blow, but low and behold, out comes a Complete Heal, and our poor little caster should now be nearly exhausted of mana, which means no way to gate. Being of the 22nd Season, I have my root spell, that I now so nicely unleash on this poor defensless caster, and continue to pound his brains in and watch in delight as his moment of triumph is ruined, and he is doomed to die at the end of my blade. <p>
I make it a point to almost always have Lay on Hands anytime I travel or go anywhere where PK's frequent. It is important to remember that most casters will not have enough mana to kill a Paladin with Lay on Hands. It's like trying to kill you twice, so any time you can take advantage of this, and gain the element of surprise, the better off you will be in the end. Instead of standing there minus a Lay Hands and a gated caster, you'll have a Dead caster at your feet, and the grim satisfaction that comes with it!!<p>
<p>
Tempus!!!</td></tr>
